[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/1894-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1894 throughout the world.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The **1894 major league baseball season** began on April 19, 1894.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 30, with the Baltimore Orioles as the pennant winner of the National League and the New York Giants as runner-up.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the first Temple Cup on October 4 and ended with Game 4 on October 8.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The Giants swept the Orioles, capturing their first Temple Cup.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The 1894 season saw the return of a postseason championship series, the Temple Cup, following the end of the World's Championship Series with the demise of the American Association in 1891 and the one-off, split-season 1892 World's Championship Series.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The 1894 schedule consisted of 132 games for the twelve teams of the National League.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 12 games against the other eleven teams in the league.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/1894-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place in the previous season and would be used until 1898.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 19 featuring eight teams.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on September 30, also featuring eight teams.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The Temple Cup took place between October 4 and October 8.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Makeshift stands built for remainder of the season, from August 18.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/1894-major-league-baseball-season] 16 tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the start of the season, the Cincinnati Reds' home as League Park saw major changes.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/1894-major-league-baseball-season] A new grandstand in what was left field was built, as well as an ampitheater.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The baseball diamond was shifted from the southeast corner of the lot to the southwest corner, with the original seating retained as right field seating.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/1895-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1895 throughout the world.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/1895-temple-cup] The **1895 Temple Cup** was an end-of-the-year best-of-seven playoff between the National League champion Baltimore Orioles and runner-up Cleveland Spiders.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/1895-temple-cup] The series began on October 2 and ended on October 8 with the Spiders winning in five games.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/1895-temple-cup] In this second iteration of the Temple Cup, the NL pennant winning Baltimore Orioles, who were also in their second Temple Cup, once again lost to the NL runner-up team.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/1896-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1896 throughout the world.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/1897-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1897 throughout the world.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/1898-major-league-baseball-season] The **1898 major league baseball season** began on April 15, 1898.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/1898-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 15, with the Boston Beaneaters as the pennant winner of the National League.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/1898-major-league-baseball-season] Due to lack of enthusiasm from both players and fans, the Temple Cup which had taken place in the four previous seasons was not held, nor was there any other form of a postseason.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/1898-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago Colts renamed as the Chicago Orphans.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/1898-major-league-baseball-season] The 1898 schedule consisted of 154 games for the twelve teams of the National League.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/1898-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 14 games against the other eleven teams in the league.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/1898-major-league-baseball-season] This format saw an increase to the previously used format, which had each team play 12 games against each other, and had resulted in a total of 132 games.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/1898-major-league-baseball-season] The 154-game format had previously been used by the National League during in 1892.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/1898-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 15 featuring six teams.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/1898-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on October 15, featuring eight teams.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/1898-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Spiders played in 15 neutral site games in which they were treated as the home team.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/1898-major-league-baseball-season] Meanwhile, blue laws restricted Sunday activities in several localities, causing several teams to play at ballparks in a different locality.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/1898-major-league-baseball-season] 24 tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/1898-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Bridegrooms, leave Eastern Park (where they played for seven seasons) and move to Washington Park, where they would go on to play for 15 seasons through 1912.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/1898-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Spiders played 15 of 57 home games (about 26%) outside of the Greater Cleveland area.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/bobby-wallace-baseball] Wallace was born in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/bobby-wallace-baseball] He made his major league debut in 1894 as a starting pitcher with the Cleveland Spiders.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/bobby-wallace-baseball] After a 12–14 record in 1895, Wallace played outfield and pitcher in 1896.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/bobby-wallace-baseball] In 1897, Wallace was an everyday player as he became the team's full-time third baseman, batted .335 and drove in 112 runs.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/bobby-wallace-baseball] Louis Perfectos (renamed the Cardinals in 1900) and changed position to shortstop.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/bobby-wallace-baseball] He hit .295 with 108 RBI and 12 home runs (second in the league behind Buck Freeman's 25).
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/bobby-wallace-baseball] Wallace changed teams again in 1902, when he joined the St.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/bobby-wallace-baseball] His playing time began decreasing a decade later, with his last season as a regular coming in 1912.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/bobby-wallace-baseball] Wallace played in just 55 games in 1913, and never played that much again for the rest of his career.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/bobby-wallace-baseball] In July 1917, he returned to the National League and the Cardinals, and played in just eight games that season.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/bobby-wallace-baseball] After batting .153 in 32 games in 1918, Wallace retired with a .268 career batting average, 1059 runs, 34 home runs, 1121 RBI and 201 stolen bases.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/bobby-wallace-baseball] He played his last game on September 2, 1918, at the age of 44 years and 312 days, making him the oldest shortstop to play in a regular-season game.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/bobby-wallace-baseball] The record was broken by Omar Vizquel on May 7, 2012.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/bobby-wallace-baseball] Wallace was generally recognized as the AL's best shortstop from 1902 to 1911, when he served briefly as Browns player-manager.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/bobby-wallace-baseball] After moving from third to short, Wallace felt he'd found his place in the infield earning the nickname "Mr.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/bobby-wallace-baseball] He would also claim to have invented the continuous throwing motion, “As more speed afoot was constantly demanded for big league ball, I noticed the many infield bounders which the runner beat to first only by the thinnest fractions of a second..
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/bobby-wallace-baseball] He played for 25 seasons, and holds the record for the longest career by a player who never played in a World Series.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/bobby-wallace-baseball] When his playing time diminished, Wallace managed and umpired.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/bobby-wallace-baseball] Louis Browns in 1911 and 1912 and the Cincinnati Reds during part of the 1937 season.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/bobby-wallace-baseball] He compiled 62 wins and 154 losses for a .287 winning percentage as a major league manager.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/bobby-wallace-baseball] He also managed the minor league Wichita Witches in 1917.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/bobby-wallace-baseball] He umpired in the American League in 1915, working 111 games.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/bobby-wallace-baseball] Wallace was inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame in 1953.
[src:bobby-wallace-baseball/bobby-wallace-baseball] Wallace died on November 3, 1960, in Torrance, California, one day shy of his 87th birthday.
